-- 
Singapore Stocks: GP Batteries, Singapore Exchange, Yongnam

-- B y   J o n a t h a n   B u r g o s
-- 
2011-06-01T05:00:14Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-01/boustead-singapore-exchange-yongnam-singapore-stocks-preview.html
Singapore’s  Straits Times Index (FSSTI)  rose
0.5 percent to 3,175.90 as of the 12:30 p.m. trading break.
Almost four stocks rose for each that fell in the benchmark
index of 30 companies.  Shares on the measure trade at an average 14.6 times
estimated earnings, compared with about 15.6 times at the end of
2010, according to data compiled by Bloomberg.  The following shares were among the most active in the
market. Stock symbols are in parentheses after the company name.  GP Batteries International Ltd. (GP)  , a maker of
rechargeable batteries, climbed 2.6 percent to S$1.20. The
company said a unit bought 1.53 million additional shares in
Danionics A/S for S$1 million ($813,471), raising its stake in
the Danish battery maker to 17.3 percent from 9.1 percent.  Otto Marine Ltd. (OTML)  , a Singapore-based shipbuilder,
declined 2.3 percent to 21 Singapore cents. The company said a
unit received a letter from Mosvold Supply Ltd., a Norwegian
operator of offshore support vessels, terminating a contract and
demanding the refund of advance payments of $26.7 million.  Singapore Exchange Ltd. (SGX)  , operator of the city’s
bourse, gained 1.2 percent to S$7.61. The company said it will
start clearing Asian foreign-exchange forwards by September. The
securities will include non-deliverable currencies in the region
such as the Chinese yuan, Indonesian rupiah, Indian rupee,
Korean won, Malaysian ringgit, Philippine peso and Taiwanese
dollar, it said.  Yongnam Holdings Ltd. (YNH)  , a Singapore-based
construction company, increased 2 percent to 26 Singapore cents.
The company said it won sub contracts, valued at S$49 million
($40 million), to provide tunneling works for the Hong Kong
section of the Express Rail Link, a high-speed train network
between the city and  China ’s mainland.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Jonathan Burgos in Singapore at 
 jburgos4@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Nick Gentle at   ngentle2@bloomberg.net . 